Method Detail

start

void start()
Starts the stop watch for the current thread. This overwrites any previous start time for the current thread. This is useful, for example, when you start timing something and an exception occurs before you have a chance to stop it. The next time you call start, it's as if the prior call never happened, which is typically what you want when you're trying to get uniform timings. You can, of course, explicitly call stop in error cases if the above is not what you want.

stop

void stop()
Stops the watch for this thread. This records the number of milliseconds since you last called start and ads that to the total elapsed time in addition to recording the extra call for future calculations of the average time for this stopwatch. This method also updates the max and the min, which are held across all threads.

stop

void stop(String description)
Stops the watch for this thread. This records the number of milliseconds since you last called start and ads that to the total elapsed time in addition to recording the extra call for future calculations of the average time for this stopwatch. This method also updates the max and the min, which are held across all threads.

Parameters:
description - A more detailed description of the watch.
